column1: The latent outcome (e.g., construct, behaviour) that is assessed, predicted, or classified.
column2: The specific outcome the models were trained to or the labelling criteria used to classify the data.
column3: The language used in the model.
column4: The type of language used (e.g., social media, probed, free-text).
column5: The level of analysis (message, person, group).
column7: Description of where the training data source comes from
column8: Description of the training data source
column9: Type of labels used in training (e.g., self-report, annotation, interview scores, behaviour, best-estimate assessments, etc...)
column10: Does the model include a language domain distribution of the training set for assessing language domain similarity with new data?
column11: Link to data if it can be openly shared
column12: Type of model used for prediction (such as ridge regression, L2 logistic regression)
column13: The features used in the model (e.g., word embeddings, topics, demographics)
column14: Metric used to validate the model
column16: Accuracy on a held-out, out-of-population test sample
column17: A Sequential Evaluation with Model Pre-registration
column18: Describe any additional metrics from the n-fold cross-validation (if any).
column19: Describe any additional metrics from the held-out (if any).
column20: Describe any additional metrics from the SEMP procedure (if any).
column21: If the research received ethical approval, add the application ID.
column22: Describe ethical considerations or concerns that went into the model development and testing.
column23: Citation for the model and/or name of the person, group or organisation developing the model.
column24: Approximate date the model was created
column25: Contact details about who to contact with questions about the model
column27: Describe the study type, such as development, replication, independent replication, extension/update of a model, or use in a new context.
column28: Indicates whether the model is original or updated since publication (e.g., using a newer LLM); details about this can be described under Miscellaneous.
column29: Describe any other relevant information or recommendations.
column31: A unique identifier for the model. Use only uncased
column32: Where the model can be accessed (e.g., OSF.io, github.com, huggingface.com)
column33: Specify how the function should handle the model argument. Setting it to “fine-tuned“ or “text-trained“ will apply their respective default behaviors, while setting it to “implicit motives“ will trigger specific steps tailored to these models.
